FL,316,300,200,140,000,100
PN,31505
SC,0005
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F315A1779267997
OL,3,CWhy are we seeing more hail even
OL,4,Cthough the weather is warming up?
OL,6,FInterestingly, if you cut a hailstone
OL,7,Fopen, under a microscope you can often
OL,8,Fsee layers inside it - like layers in
OL,9,Fan onion - showing how it grew during
OL,10,Frepeated journeys through the storm
OL,11,Fcloud.
OL,13,FEventually these hailstones get too
OL,14,Fheavy and fall to the ground - which
OL,15,Fis what we would then call a hailstorm.
OL,17,FThe warmer the temperature, the
OL,18,Fstronger the updraught and larger the
OL,19,Fhailstones can grow ` which is why
OL,20,Fhail is more common during the warmer
OL,21,Fmonths.
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G5/10
