OL,3,CWhy are we seeing more hail even
OL,4,Cthough the weather is warming up?
OL,6,FHow does hail create thunder and
OL,7,Flightning?
OL,9,FI think this is the immensely cool bit!
OL,11,FRemember how the little balls of hail
OL,12,Fget thrown around inside thunderclouds?
OL,14,FWell, as they swirl around, they knock
OL,15,Finto each other creating static
OL,16,Felectricity.
OL,18,FAfter a time, the electrical energy
OL,19,Fdischarges in a rapid burst of
OL,20,Flightning.
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G6/10
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,316,300,200,140,000,100
PN,31507
SC,0007
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F315A1779267997
OL,3,CWhy are we seeing more hail even
OL,4,Cthough the weather is warming up?
OL,6,FAs that electricity shoots through the
OL,7,Fair, the superheated air expands - and
OL,8,Fthat creates a very loud noise which
OL,9,Fwe call thunder.
OL,11,FLight travels almost a million times
OL,12,Ffaster than sound so we see lightning
OL,13,Fbefore we hear it (thunder).
OL,15,FI told you it was cool, right?!
OL,17,FThis is precisely why we so often get
OL,18,Fwhat forecasters call 'a thundery
OL,19,Fbreakdown' at the end of a spell of
OL,20,Fvery warm weather.
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G7/10
